                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 58.&#8212;<name type="person"
                                                key="850">Horace Hill</name>, a robust muscular man,
                                        age 25 years; colored; was admitted <date type="admit"
                                                when="1865-11-07">November 7, 1865</date>, with
                                        quotidian intermittent fever; tongue yellow-coated; appetite
                                        poor; pulse during the intervals of the paroxysm 84, full
                                        and of good strength; bowels quite regular; urine scanty and
                                        of high color; no difficulty of breathing; no &#339;dema
                                        of the feet and legs. After treatment for two days the
                                        chills left the patient, but a febrile pulse remained; two
                                        days later sordes appeared on the teeth and lips, and the
                                        tongue became exceedingly dry; mental torpor and slight
                                        delirium were manifested. There was <choice><orig>fulness</orig><reg>fullness</reg></choice>
                                        and slight
                                        tenderness on pressure in the right hypochondrium and
                                        greater precordial <choice><orig>dulness</orig><reg>dullness</reg></choice>
                                        than natural. Moderate vomiting
                                        took place about noon of the <date type="death"
                                                when="1865-11-13">13th</date>, and in a few minutes
                                        the patient suddenly and unexpectedly died. <hi
                                                rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination sixteen
                                        hours after death: The right ventricle of the heart much
                                        dilated; spleen greatly enlarged and softened; liver much
                                        enlarged; kidneys fatty; other organs normal.&#8212;<hi
                                                rend="italic"><name type="person" key="134">Surgeon
                                                  Edwin Bentley</name>, <name type="organization"
                                                  key="132">U. S. Vols.</name>, <name
                                                  type="hospital" key="210">L'Ouverture
                                                          Hospital</name>, <name type="place">Alexandria, Va.</name></hi></p>
                        
